arch:property.oc:show_val: The cistern wall is composed of bedrock on its south and east faces. Only the north and west faces have seen construction and reconstruction over time. The condition of the walls is excellent. Lined with a dark gray hydraulic plaster, which added an additional binder to the walls, the present condition of the surface is excellent. The north and west walls were laid with wet mortar and also surfaced (and re-surfaced) with hydraulic plaster. The number of ashlar courses could not be determined from the examination of the interior, but the north and west walls were laid in the typical Nabataean fashion with two casemate walls, but in this case there was a doubling of the walls and there were probably four courses of stones, or two casemate walls constructed back to back—in actual fact three courses of two walls, or in toto six courses. Of interest is that the west wall appears to remain strong, as if it might be reinforced and reused in the present.
Opening elevation: 904.152 m At Sub Datum P in the south.
Interior measurements —37.8 square meters (7.00 m north south-by-5.40 m east west).

In the north 0.80 m, in the south 2.85 m in the east 2.50 m, and in the west 2.85 m. The average of these dimensions, 1.96 m was used to calculate the holding capacity of the Cistern-Reservoir at 19,571.979 gallons of water.
